    <div class="contain">
        <div class="main-content">
            <div class="card">
                <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
                <p>
                    Odissi is one of the oldest classical dance forms of India, originating in the temples of Odisha.
                    It was performed as a devotional act dedicated to Lord Jagannath. The dance embodies grace,
                    spirituality, and expressive storytelling, keeping ancient traditions alive.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Dance Elements</h2>
                <p>
                    Odissi combines intricate footwork, fluid hand gestures (mudras), and expressive facial movements.
                    The dance is known for its tribhangi posture and graceful transitions, capturing emotions through
                    its storytelling techniques based on mythological themes.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Music and Attire</h2>
                <p>
                    The dance is accompanied by traditional Odissi music, featuring instruments like the mardala,
                    flute, and violin. Dancers wear elaborate silk sarees, intricate silver jewelry, and headpieces,
                    adding to the visual appeal of the performance.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Renowned Artists</h2>
                <p>
                    Legendary Odissi dancers like Kelucharan Mohapatra, Sanjukta Panigrahi, and Sonal Mansingh have
                    contributed immensely to its global recognition. Their performances have elevated Odissi to an
                    international stage.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Performance Venues</h2>
                <p>
                    Odissi performances are a highlight in festivals like Konark Dance Festival and Mukteshwar Dance
                    Festival. Major cultural centers and auditoriums in Odisha also host grand Odissi showcases,
                    keeping the dance form vibrant and evolving.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

